CITL is making ~7,000 defects/vulns, across 3,243 Ubuntu APT packages, available to package maintainers.

<!--more-->

CITL is releasing these defects in the following way: There is a complete list in this blog post. In fact there are two lists. One list is ordered by the target application and it’s package. This is called the TARGET LIST. It counts the number of unique and distinct faults[1](#1) in the target itself (including threads, subprocesses etc.). The other list, called the MODULE LIST,  includes faults in the associated binaries that may not be under the direct control of the package maintainer (e.g. libraries etc.). To find your package, or target application etc., just CTRL-F in this web page.

We are also providing files for each of the lists for your downloading pleasure.

If you are a package maintainer, or somehow otherwise involved in an obvious and verifiable way with the package, we are willing to provide the following described information regarding the code defect to you. Please contact us ( contact@cyber-itl.org ) from an email address we can verify is connected with the project or package maintainer list if possible. If this is not possible we would appreciate that the requests include some method or form of verification. If the volume of requests we receive is large enough, we plan to work with a third party partner for verification and distribution of information and reproduction data to the maintainers (contact us if you would like to be the third party organization that would perform this public service).

The lists of defects/vulns themselves are hopefully relatively self explanatory. The fields include:

### Target List:

```
Id|package|path|crash count|signals
```

### Module List:

```
Id|package|path|crash count|signals
```

All of the crashes have been qualified and verified as reproducible and are expected to be largely distinct items.

The information we have all came from automated static and dynamic analysis of the binaries. From our data we are making available to package maintainers:

- Environment variables, file contents, and input requirements to trigger the defect (within a JSON file)
- Input corpus that causes the defect
- Wrapper programs, when able to be automatically created, for easier reproduction[2](#2)
- Rich static analysis of the target binary (numerous artifacts reflecting the binary under test)

## Here’s what we are *not* providing beyond the data mentioned above:


We are *not* providing additional support to recreate, remediate, or classify/rank the severity.


## Why isn’t CITL providing further support to the package maintainers?


While CITL doesn’t particularly want to see software remain vulnerable or flawed, it is not CITL’s mission to improve the software itself. CITL’s mission is to create scientific, quantifiable, and reproducible ways to measure software binaries to understand how fragile or robust they may be. The work CITL performs is ultimately to allow *consumers* (for a wide definition of consumers) to evaluate software the software they use or intend to use. All of this work is designed to happen behind the scenes, as CITL was never designed for high-touch interfacing.


## Why release the information, and why in this particular fashion?

We were internally split between three options:

#### A)

Do not make the results available at all. CITL created the internal data sets (of which this is a very small subset) for our own needs for analysis and research. Not making any of the direct findings available was a viable option, but we felt we could do a little better and wanted to contribute to the larger community.

#### B)

Make all of the raw data publicly available as large dumps. We were pretty sure some of the items would be made use of… possibly in a painful way, but likely resulting in fixes. This seemed less neighborly, but historically this has worked to ultimately result in patches and/or people moving away from the software in question. Short term pain long term gain?

#### C)

Do something in-between. Make metadata about the software defects in a bunch of packages publicly available. Hand off the details and datasets needed by the package maintainers to classify and reproduce the problem to directly help improve the ecosystem.


We chose C. Hopefully it turns out to be a good enough call.


## Why did CITL choose to perform analysis on the APT repository? Also, why did you perform all of the measurements on compiled binaries instead of from source?

The CITL Analysis system has three main components: a rich static-analysis system, a dynamic analysis system, and an analytics environment. All of these were designed to run on targets where no source code is available. CITL needed millions of target binaries (applications and libraries) for the static analysis and something statistically significant for dynamically analyzed subsets.

APT ended up representing a good “smoke test”. There is a wide range of software types and programs that would stress test the CITL system and CITL could grab large numbers of targets in binary form. We mirrored the Ubuntu 18.04 APT repository from earlier this year and used that as our test bench.

There may be other runs against large datasets in the future. The system is designed to be able to target and process entire portfolios from software companies, ingest the ~10k of binaries and libraries that make up the user space of an entire operating system, or collect and statically and dynamically evaluate software representing an entire sector (finance, infrastructure, healthcare, etc.).

Put another way: CITL’s goal is to have enough rich static analysis and dynamic (fuzzing and security evaluation during runtime) that it is possible to perform analysis to identify characteristics of software applications that are strongly correlated with fragile, or robust, products. For such a goal, access to source code could not be a requirement or dependency.


## How do I get in touch to get the information?



```
contact@cyber-itl.org
Subject: APT-REPOSITORY DEFECT REQUEST for ${XXX}
```

Please include your return e-mail and some way that easily shows you are associated with the package. We will then respond with reproduction information, tools and data that might be needed to identify the defects.

## Footnotes

### 1
We can’t promise they are 100% distinct but our system qualifies, reproduces, and believes them to be unique.

### 2
As our automated dynamic analysis performs continuous input discovery, the environment that triggers the defect is sometimes non-trivial. The C-wrapper program attempts to recreate the environment, input files, arguments, etc. to trigger the fault and then execve’s the target program. There are several ways of controlling this wrapper program which are described in its command line help output. Usually you can just attach a debugger to the wrapper and, as the wrapper overlays itself with the target program once the environment is set, nothing else needs to be done to reach the fault.
